## 2. Architecture Decision: Shared Component System

### Option A: Vanilla HTML + Shared ES Modules (RECOMMENDED ✅)
**Approach:** Extract shared CSS/JS into importable ES modules. Each page stays as a self-contained HTML file but imports shared infrastructure.

```
/shared/
  core.css          ← unified design tokens, reset, typography, utilities
  components.css    ← buttons, cards, inputs, modals, toasts, badges, tables
  layout.css        ← global nav, sidebar patterns, page layouts
  core.js           ← auth guard, API client, toast, escape, timeAgo, etc.
  ws-manager.js     ← WebSocket with reconnect, heartbeat, event system
  markdown.js       ← shared marked.js + hljs + XSS-safe rendering
  nav.js            ← global navigation component (renders sidebar/topbar)
```

**Pros:**
- Zero build tools needed (ES modules work natively in all modern browsers)
- Minimal diff from current code — pages keep their structure
- Can be done incrementally — don't need to rewrite everything at once
- VPS-friendly: no node_modules, no webpack, no build step
- Self-hosted fonts/icons already partially in /shared/

**Cons:**
- No component reactivity (state management is manual)
- Repeated DOM manipulation code

**Effort:** 8-12 hours for shared infrastructure, then 1-3 hours per page migration

### Option B: Alpine.js Micro-Framework
**Pros:** Reactive UI without build tools, `x-data` declarative syntax
**Cons:** Learning curve, all 18 pages need rewriting, ~30KB added, overkill for most pages
**Effort:** 20-30 hours total

### Option C: Petite-Vue / Lit
**Pros:** Component system, slots, reactivity
**Cons:** Build tools often needed for production, higher complexity
**Effort:** 30-40 hours

### Option D: Full React/Vue/Svelte Rewrite
**Pros:** Proper component system, state management, ecosystem
**Cons:** Requires build pipeline, heavy RAM usage on VPS, weeks of work, completely different DX
**Effort:** 80-120 hours
**REJECTED** — Lucy needs speed, VPS has 8GB, no build pipeline wanted

### **Decision: Option A** — Vanilla HTML + Shared ES Modules
This gives 80% of the benefit at 20% of the cost. It's the sweet spot for this VPS, this team size, and this timeline.

